<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="45" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
Very closely related to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. wilverthi" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wilverthi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. wilverthi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a species widespread in the Congo basin and the Albertine Rift. 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. biaculeata" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="biaculeata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. biaculeata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. has the 10th abdominal tergite deeply split into two lobes (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 29–35" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 29 - 35. Morphological details of male Poreuomena biaculeata sp. nov. Habitus (29), left tegminal flap with stridulatory file on the underside (30), stridulatory file on the underside of the left tegminal flap (31), abdominal apex in lateral (32) and rear view (33), cerci (34), subgenital plate (35)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures29-35" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499185" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">33</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 29–35" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 29 - 35. Morphological details of male Poreuomena biaculeata sp. nov. Habitus (29), left tegminal flap with stridulatory file on the underside (30), stridulatory file on the underside of the left tegminal flap (31), abdominal apex in lateral (32) and rear view (33), cerci (34), subgenital plate (35)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures29-35" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499185" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">34</figureCitation>
), while in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. wilverthi" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wilverthi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. wilverthi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the 10th abdominal tergite is not divided as deeply, just at the apex however, with a median groove. The cerci in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. wilverthi" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wilverthi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. wilverthi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are thick but smoothly tapering to the apex with an acute tip (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 101–107" captionStartId="F20" captionText="Figures 101 - 107. Morphological details of male Poreuomena wilverthi. Habitus (101, syntype, 102), stridulatory file on the underside of the left tegmen (103), lateral view on apex (104), subgenital plate (105), apex ventral-lateral (106) and dorsal-lateral view (107)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures101-107" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499199" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">105</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 101–107" captionStartId="F20" captionText="Figures 101 - 107. Morphological details of male Poreuomena wilverthi. Habitus (101, syntype, 102), stridulatory file on the underside of the left tegmen (103), lateral view on apex (104), subgenital plate (105), apex ventral-lateral (106) and dorsal-lateral view (107)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures101-107" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499199" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">106</figureCitation>
), while in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. biaculeata" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="biaculeata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. biaculeata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., the cerci are thick at the base and then suddenly narrowing midway forming a finger-like but pointed and sclerotized apical section (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 29–35" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 29 - 35. Morphological details of male Poreuomena biaculeata sp. nov. Habitus (29), left tegminal flap with stridulatory file on the underside (30), stridulatory file on the underside of the left tegminal flap (31), abdominal apex in lateral (32) and rear view (33), cerci (34), subgenital plate (35)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures29-35" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499185" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">32-34</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. biaculeata" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="biaculeata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. biaculeata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. is also closely related to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. crassipes" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassipes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. crassipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with a similar tegminal flap of the 10th abdominal tergite but differently shaped cerci.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="45" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Male.</emphasis>
Typical 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1878" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Poreuomena" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Poreuomena" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Poreuomena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species with wings protruding over the body by only a few mm (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 29–35" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 29 - 35. Morphological details of male Poreuomena biaculeata sp. nov. Habitus (29), left tegminal flap with stridulatory file on the underside (30), stridulatory file on the underside of the left tegminal flap (31), abdominal apex in lateral (32) and rear view (33), cerci (34), subgenital plate (35)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures29-35" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499185" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">29</figureCitation>
). Where tegmina meet, when folded, interior part of cells of dark colour while surrounding and elevated veins green (tawny in preserved insect). Rs branching off in the first half of the basal part of the tegmen. Tegmina with two flaps at their base, the flap of the left wing smaller and more pointed than the broader flap with a rounded tip on the right tegmen. The stridulatory rib marked dark brown on the flap of the left tegmen, uniformly brown on the right tegmen. Beneath flaps, tegmina with narrow longish, oval brown markings. Stridulatory file on the underside of left flap about 1.1 mm long; teeth at the apical part of the left flap very densely set and gradually getting larger to the middle of the file where the teeth are largest and widely set. At the end of the file at the interior part, strongly curved with small and a few widely set teeth; with about 20 widely and in the middle large teeth, apically more than 30 very densely set teeth (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 29–35" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 29 - 35. Morphological details of male Poreuomena biaculeata sp. nov. Habitus (29), left tegminal flap with stridulatory file on the underside (30), stridulatory file on the underside of the left tegminal flap (31), abdominal apex in lateral (32) and rear view (33), cerci (34), subgenital plate (35)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures29-35" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499185" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">31</figureCitation>
). Stridulatory file on the right tegminal flap not as strongly developed but of similar shape and the same arrangement of the teeth. The 10th abdominal tergite of typical bilobate form, deeply divided medially thus forming two processes with upcurved posterior parts (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 29–35" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 29 - 35. Morphological details of male Poreuomena biaculeata sp. nov. Habitus (29), left tegminal flap with stridulatory file on the underside (30), stridulatory file on the underside of the left tegminal flap (31), abdominal apex in lateral (32) and rear view (33), cerci (34), subgenital plate (35)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures29-35" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499185" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">33</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 29–35" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 29 - 35. Morphological details of male Poreuomena biaculeata sp. nov. Habitus (29), left tegminal flap with stridulatory file on the underside (30), stridulatory file on the underside of the left tegminal flap (31), abdominal apex in lateral (32) and rear view (33), cerci (34), subgenital plate (35)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures29-35" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499185" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">34</figureCitation>
). Cerci thick at the base, then strongly narrowing and forming a sclerotised pointed apical tip (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 29–35" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 29 - 35. Morphological details of male Poreuomena biaculeata sp. nov. Habitus (29), left tegminal flap with stridulatory file on the underside (30), stridulatory file on the underside of the left tegminal flap (31), abdominal apex in lateral (32) and rear view (33), cerci (34), subgenital plate (35)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures29-35" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499185" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">33</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 29–35" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 29 - 35. Morphological details of male Poreuomena biaculeata sp. nov. Habitus (29), left tegminal flap with stridulatory file on the underside (30), stridulatory file on the underside of the left tegminal flap (31), abdominal apex in lateral (32) and rear view (33), cerci (34), subgenital plate (35)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures29-35" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499185" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">34</figureCitation>
). Subgenital plate with two slender but short lobes (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 29–35" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 29 - 35. Morphological details of male Poreuomena biaculeata sp. nov. Habitus (29), left tegminal flap with stridulatory file on the underside (30), stridulatory file on the underside of the left tegminal flap (31), abdominal apex in lateral (32) and rear view (33), cerci (34), subgenital plate (35)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures29-35" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499185" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">35</figureCitation>
). Titillators present (two slender long structures), protruding between the subgenital plate and the cerci (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 29–35" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 29 - 35. Morphological details of male Poreuomena biaculeata sp. nov. Habitus (29), left tegminal flap with stridulatory file on the underside (30), stridulatory file on the underside of the left tegminal flap (31), abdominal apex in lateral (32) and rear view (33), cerci (34), subgenital plate (35)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures29-35" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499185" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">32</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Female.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
